ng an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Castile","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of   Casteel   1, a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Casteel","meanings":["Altered form of mainly northern French <b>Ducastel</b>: topographic name, with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’, from Picard <i>castel</i>, Old French <i>chastel</i> ‘castle’ (see   Castel   5, compare 2 below); or a habitational name for someone from any of several places called Le Castel. Compare   Castile  .","Dutch: from <i>kasteel</i> ‘castle’, hence a topographic name or a metonymic occupational name for someone who lived or worked in a castle."]}]},{"name":"Ferdinand","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Spanish name, originally <i>Ferdinando</i> (now <i>Hernán</i>), which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin, derived from <i>farð</i> ‘journey’ (or possibly an altered form of <i>frið</i> ‘peace’) + <i>nand</i> ‘ready, prepared’. This was a traditional name in the royal families of Spain from an early date. It appeared in Britain in the 16th century, having been introduced by Roman Catholic supporters of  Queen Mary I , who married  Philip II  of Spain in  1554 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fernand","meanings":["From a Spanish name, originally <i>Ferdinando</i> (now <i>Hernán</i>), which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin, derived from <i>farð</i> ‘journey’ (or possibly an altered form of <i>frið</i> ‘peace’) + <i>nand</i> ‘ready, prepared’. This was a traditional name in the royal families of Spain from an early date. It appeared in Britain in the 16th century, having been introduced by Roman Catholic supporters of  Queen Mary I , who married  Philip II  of Spain in  1554 ."]}]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Dorothea  , also used independently."],"variants":[]},{"name":"great,","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of <i>Margareta</i>, a Latinate form of   Margaret .  As an independent given name it became fairly popular in the English-speaking world as a result of the fame of the Swedish-born film actress  Greta Garbo  (  1905–92 , born  Greta Louisa Gustafsson )."],"variants":[{"name":"Gretta","meanings":["Short form of <i>Margareta</i>, a Latinate form of   Margaret .  As an independent given name it became fairly popular in the English-speaking world as a result of the fame of the Swedish-born film actress  Greta Garbo  (  1905–92 , born  Greta Louisa Gustafsson )."]}]},{"name":"Count","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earl","meanings":["North American: from the title originally adopted as a nickname parallel to   Duke  ,   King  , etc. The title was used in England in Norman times as an equivalent of the French <i>comte</i> ‘count’ it is from Old English <i>eorl</i> ‘warrior, nobleman, prince’. In some cases the given name may have been taken from the surname <i>Earl</i>, which was originally either a nickname or a term denoting someone who worked in the household of an earl."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ferdinand I, the great, Count of Castile was born in 1015 as the son of Sancho III Garces, the Great, King of Navarre and Muniadona of Castile. He had at least 1 son with Sancha VON LEON. He died on 24 June 1065, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1015–24 Jun 1065":"1015–24. juuni 1